[src:graphql-js/api-fetch] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:graphql-js/api-fetch] It’s been available across browsers since March 2017.
[src:graphql-js/api-fetch] The **`fetch()`** method of the `Window` interface starts the process of fetching a resource from the network, returning a promise that is fulfilled once the response is available.
[src:graphql-js/api-fetch] The promise resolves to the `Response` object representing the response to your request.
[src:graphql-js/api-fetch] A `fetch()` promise only rejects when the request fails, for example, because of a badly-formed request URL or a network error.
[src:graphql-js/api-fetch] A `fetch()` promise *does not* reject if the server responds with HTTP status codes that indicate errors (`404`, `504`, etc.).
[src:graphql-js/api-fetch] Instead, a `then()` handler must check the `Response.ok` and/or `Response.status` properties.
[src:graphql-js/api-fetch] The `fetch()` method is controlled by the `connect-src` directive of Content Security Policy rather than the directive of the resources it's retrieving.
[src:graphql-js/api-fetch] This defines the resource that you wish to fetch.
[src:graphql-js/api-fetch] A `RequestInit` object containing any custom settings that you want to apply to the request.
[src:graphql-js/api-fetch] A `Promise` that resolves to a `Response` object.
[src:graphql-js/api-fetch] The request was aborted due to a call to the `AbortController` `abort()` method.
[src:graphql-js/api-fetch] In our Fetch Request example (see Fetch Request live) we create a new `Request` object using the relevant constructor, then fetch it using a `fetch()` call.
[src:graphql-js/api-fetch] Since we are fetching an image, we run `Response.blob()` on the response to give it the proper MIME type so it will be handled properly, then create an Object URL of it and display it in an `<img>` element.
[src:graphql-js/api-fetch] In our Fetch Request with init example (see Fetch Request init live) we do the same thing except that we pass in an *options* object when we invoke `fetch()`.
[src:graphql-js/api-fetch] The Using fetch article provides more examples of using `fetch()`.
[src:graphql-js/api] An **application programming interface** (**API**) is a connection between computers or between computer programs.
[src:graphql-js/api] It is a type of software interface, offering a service to other pieces of software.
[src:graphql-js/api] A document or standard that describes how to build such a connection or interface is called an *API specification*.
[src:graphql-js/api] A computer system that meets this standard is said to *implement* or *expose* an API.
[src:graphql-js/api] The term API may refer either to the specification or to the implementation.
[src:graphql-js/api] In contrast to a user interface, which connects a computer to a person, an application programming interface connects computers or pieces of software to each other.
[src:graphql-js/api] It is not intended to be used directly by a person (the end user) other than a computer programmer who is incorporating it into software.
[src:graphql-js/api] An API is often made up of different parts which act as tools or services that are available to the programmer.
[src:graphql-js/api] A program or a programmer that uses one of these parts is said to *call* that portion of the API.
[src:graphql-js/api] The calls that make up the API are also known as subroutines, methods, requests, or endpoints.
[src:graphql-js/api] An API specification *defines* these calls, meaning that it explains how to use or implement them.
[src:graphql-js/api] One of the main purpose of APIs is to hide the internal details of how a system works, exposing only those parts a programmer will find useful and keeping them consistent even if the internal details later change.
[src:graphql-js/api] An API may be custom-built for a particular pair of systems, or it may be a shared standard allowing interoperability among many systems.
[src:graphql-js/api] The term API is often used to refer to web APIs, which allow communication between computers that are joined by the internet.
[src:graphql-js/api] There are also APIs for programming languages, software libraries, computer operating systems, and computer hardware.
[src:graphql-js/api] APIs originated in the 1940s, though the term did not emerge until the 1960s and 70s.
[src:graphql-js/api] An API opens a software system to interactions from the outside.
[src:graphql-js/api] It allows two software systems to communicate across a boundary — an interface — using mutually agreed-upon signals.
[src:graphql-js/api] In other words, an API connects software entities together.
[src:graphql-js/api] Unlike a user interface, an API is typically not visible to users.
[src:graphql-js/api] It is an "under the hood" portion of a software system, used for machine-to-machine communication.
[src:graphql-js/api] A well-designed API exposes only objects or actions needed by software or software developers.
[src:graphql-js/api] This abstraction simplifies programming.
[src:graphql-js/api] Building software using APIs has been compared to using building-block toys, such as Lego bricks.
[src:graphql-js/api] Software services or software libraries are analogous to the bricks; they may be joined together via their APIs, composing a new software product.
[src:graphql-js/api] The process of joining is called *integration*.
[src:graphql-js/api] As an example, consider a weather sensor that offers an API.
[src:graphql-js/api] When a certain message is transmitted to the sensor, it will detect the current weather conditions and reply with a weather report.
[src:graphql-js/api] The message that activates the sensor is an API *call*, and the weather report is an API *response*.
[src:graphql-js/api] A weather forecasting app might integrate with a number of weather sensor APIs, gathering weather data from throughout a geographical area.
[src:graphql-js/api] It represents an agreement between parties: a service provider who offers the API and the software developers who rely upon it.
[src:graphql-js/api] If the API remains stable, or if it changes only in predictable ways, developers' confidence in the API will increase.
[src:graphql-js/api] The term *API* initially described an interface only for end-user-facing programs, known as application programs.
[src:graphql-js/api] This origin is still reflected in the name "application programming interface." Today, the term is broader, including also utility software and even hardware interfaces.
[src:graphql-js/api] The idea of the API is much older than the term itself.
[src:graphql-js/api] British computer scientists Maurice Wilkes and David Wheeler worked on a modular software library in the 1940s for EDSAC, an early computer.
[src:graphql-js/api] The subroutines in this library were stored on punched paper tape organized in a filing cabinet.
[src:graphql-js/api] This cabinet also contained what Wilkes and Wheeler called a "library catalog" of notes about each subroutine and how to incorporate it into a program.
[src:graphql-js/api] Today, such a catalog would be called an API (or an API specification or API documentation) because it instructs a programmer on how to use (or "call") each subroutine that the programmer needs.
[src:graphql-js/api] Wilkes and Wheeler's book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer* contains the first published API specification.
[src:graphql-js/api] Joshua Bloch considers that Wilkes and Wheeler "latently invented" the API, because it is more of a concept that is discovered than invented.
[src:graphql-js/api] The term "application program interface" (without an *-ing* suffix) is first recorded in a paper called *Data structures and techniques for remote computer graphics* presented at an AFIPS conference in 1968.
[src:graphql-js/api] The authors of this paper use the term to describe the interaction of an application—a graphics program in this case—with the rest of the computer system.
[src:graphql-js/api] A consistent application interface (consisting of Fortran subroutine calls) was intended to free the programmer from dealing with idiosyncrasies of the graphics display device, and to provide hardware independence if the computer or the display were replaced.
[src:graphql-js/api] The term was introduced to the field of databases by C.
[src:graphql-js/api] Date in a 1974 paper called *The Relational and Network Approaches: Comparison of the Application Programming Interface*.
[src:graphql-js/api] An API became a part of the ANSI/SPARC framework for database management systems.
[src:graphql-js/api] This framework treated the application programming interface separately from other interfaces, such as the query interface.
[src:graphql-js/api] Database professionals in the 1970s observed these different interfaces could be combined; a sufficiently rich application interface could support the other interfaces as well.
[src:graphql-js/api] This observation led to APIs that supported all types of programming, not just application programming.
[src:graphql-js/api] By 1990, the API was defined simply as "a set of services available to a programmer for performing certain tasks" by technologist Carl Malamud.
[src:graphql-js/api] The idea of the API was expanded again with the dawn of remote procedure calls and web APIs.
[src:graphql-js/api] As computer networks became common in the 1970s and 80s, programmers wanted to call libraries located not only on their local computers, but on computers located elsewhere.
[src:graphql-js/api] These remote procedure calls were well supported by the Java language in particular.
[src:graphql-js/api] In the 1990s, with the spread of the internet, standards like CORBA, COM, and DCOM competed to become the most common way to expose API services.
[src:graphql-js/api] XML and JSON web APIs saw widespread commercial adoption beginning in 2000 and continuing as of 2021.
[src:graphql-js/api] The web API is now the most common meaning of the term API.
[src:graphql-js/api] The Semantic Web proposed by Tim Berners-Lee in 2001 included "semantic APIs" that recast the API as an open, distributed data interface rather than a software behavior interface.
[src:graphql-js/api] Proprietary interfaces and agents became more widespread than open ones, but the idea of the API as a data interface took hold.
[src:graphql-js/api] Because web APIs are widely used to exchange data of all kinds online, API has become a broad term describing much of the communication on the internet.
[src:graphql-js/api] When used in this way, the term API has overlap in meaning with the term communication protocol.
[src:graphql-js/api] The interface to a software library is one type of API.
[src:graphql-js/api] The API describes and prescribes the "expected behavior" (a specification) while the library is an "actual implementation" of this set of rules.
[src:graphql-js/api] A single API can have multiple implementations (or none, being abstract) in the form of different libraries that share the same programming interface.
[src:graphql-js/api] The separation of the API from its implementation can allow programs written in one language to use a library written in another.
[src:graphql-js/api] For example, because Scala and Java compile to compatible bytecode, Scala developers can take advantage of any Java API.
[src:graphql-js/api] API use can vary depending on the type of programming language involved.
[src:graphql-js/api] An API for a procedural language such as Lua could consist primarily of basic routines to execute code, manipulate data or handle errors while an API for an object-oriented language, such as Java, would provide a specification of classes and its class methods.
[src:graphql-js/api] By mapping the features and capabilities of one language to an interface implemented in another language, a language binding allows a library or service written in one language to be used when developing in another language.
[src:graphql-js/api] Tools such as SWIG and F2PY, a Fortran-to-Python interface generator, facilitate the creation of such interfaces.
[src:graphql-js/api] Moreover, the overall program flow of control can be out of the control of the caller and in the framework's hands by inversion of control or a similar mechanism.
[src:graphql-js/api] An API can specify the interface between an application and the operating system.
[src:graphql-js/api] POSIX, for example, specifies a set of common APIs that aim to enable an application written for a POSIX conformant operating system to be compiled for another POSIX conformant operating system.
[src:graphql-js/api] Linux and Berkeley Software Distribution are examples of operating systems that implement the POSIX APIs.
[src:graphql-js/api] Microsoft has shown a strong commitment to a backward-compatible API, particularly within its Windows API (Win32) library, so older applications may run on newer versions of Windows using an executable-specific setting called "Compatibility Mode".
[src:graphql-js/api] How much Microsoft developers' access to the company's operating systems' internal APIs is an advantage is unclear.
[src:graphql-js/api] Shaffer of *Technologic Computer Letter* in 1987 compared the situation to a baseball game in which "Microsoft owns all the bats and the field", and large vendors like Lotus Development and Ashton-Tate reportedly received information about MS-DOS 5.0 that smaller software developers did not.
[src:graphql-js/api] Ed Esber of Ashton-Tate said in a 1987 interview, however, that Bill Gates told him that his developers sometimes had to rewrite software based on early APIs.
[src:graphql-js/api] Gates noted in the interview that Microsoft's Apple Macintosh applications were more successful than those for MS-DOS, because his company did not have to also devote resources to Mac OS.
[src:graphql-js/api] An API differs from an application binary interface (ABI) in that an API is source code based while an ABI is binary based.
[src:graphql-js/api] For instance, POSIX provides APIs while the Linux Standard Base provides an ABI.
[src:graphql-js/api] Remote APIs allow developers to manipulate remote resources through protocols, specific standards for communication that allow different technologies to work together, regardless of language or platform.
[src:graphql-js/api] Therefore, remote APIs are useful in maintaining the object abstraction in object-oriented programming; a method call, executed locally on a proxy object, invokes the corresponding method on the remote object, using the remoting protocol, and acquires the result to be used locally as a return value.
[src:graphql-js/api] A modification of the proxy object will also result in a corresponding modification of the remote object.
[src:graphql-js/api] Web APIs are the defined interfaces through which interactions happen between an enterprise and applications that use its assets, which also is a Service Level Agreement (SLA) to specify the functional provider and expose the service path or URL for its API users.
[src:graphql-js/api] An API approach is an architectural approach that revolves around providing a program interface to a set of services to different applications serving different types of consumers.
[src:graphql-js/api] An example might be a shipping company API that can be added to an eCommerce-focused website to facilitate ordering shipping services and automatically include current shipping rates, without the site developer having to enter the shipper's rate table into a web database.
[src:graphql-js/api] Part of this trend is related to the Semantic Web movement toward Resource Description Framework (RDF), a concept to promote web-based ontology engineering technologies.
[src:graphql-js/api] Web APIs allow the combination of multiple APIs into new applications known as mashups.
[src:graphql-js/api] In the social media space, web APIs have allowed web communities to facilitate sharing content and data between communities and applications.
[src:graphql-js/api] In this way, content that is created in one place dynamically can be posted and updated to multiple locations on the web.
[src:graphql-js/api] For example, Twitter's REST API allows developers to access core Twitter data and the Search API provides methods for developers to interact with Twitter Search and trends data.
[src:graphql-js/api] The design of an API has significant impact on its usage.
[src:graphql-js/api] The principle of information hiding describes the role of programming interfaces as enabling modular programming by hiding the implementation details of the modules so that users of modules need not understand the complexities inside the modules.
[src:graphql-js/api] Thus, the design of an API attempts to provide only the tools a user would expect.
[src:graphql-js/api] The design of programming interfaces represents an important part of software architecture, the organization of a complex piece of software.
[src:graphql-js/api] APIs are one of the more common ways technology companies integrate.
[src:graphql-js/api] Those that provide and use APIs are considered as being members of a business ecosystem.
[src:graphql-js/api] An important factor when an API becomes public is its "interface stability".
[src:graphql-js/api] Changes to the API—for example adding new parameters to a function call—could break compatibility with the clients that depend on that API.
[src:graphql-js/api] When parts of a publicly presented API are subject to change and thus not stable, such parts of a particular API should be documented explicitly as "unstable".
[src:graphql-js/api] For example, in the Google Guava library, the parts that are considered unstable, and that might change soon, are marked with the Java annotation `@Beta`.
[src:graphql-js/api] A public API can sometimes declare parts of itself as *deprecated* or rescinded.
[src:graphql-js/api] This usually means that part of the API should be considered a candidate for being removed, or modified in a backward incompatible way.
[src:graphql-js/api] Therefore, these changes allow developers to transition away from parts of the API that will be removed or not supported in the future.
[src:graphql-js/api] Client code may contain innovative or opportunistic usages that were not intended by the API designers.
[src:graphql-js/api] In other words, for a library with a significant user base, when an element becomes part of the public API, it may be used in diverse ways.
[src:graphql-js/api] On February 19, 2020, Akamai published their annual “State of the Internet” report, showcasing the growing trend of cybercriminals targeting public API platforms at financial services worldwide.
[src:graphql-js/api] From December 2017 through November 2019, Akamai witnessed 85.42 billion credential violation attacks.
[src:graphql-js/api] About 20%, or 16.55 billion, were against hostnames defined as API endpoints.
[src:graphql-js/api] Of these, 473.5 million have targeted financial services sector organizations.
[src:graphql-js/api] API documentation describes what services an API offers and how to use those services, aiming to cover everything a client would need to know for practical purposes.
[src:graphql-js/api] Documentation is crucial for the development and maintenance of applications using the API.
[src:graphql-js/api] API documentation is traditionally found in documentation files but can also be found in social media such as blogs, forums, and Q&A websites.
[src:graphql-js/api] Traditional documentation files are often presented via a documentation system, such as Javadoc or Pydoc, that has a consistent appearance and structure.
[src:graphql-js/api] However, the types of content included in the documentation differs from API to API.
[src:graphql-js/api] In the interest of clarity, API documentation may include a description of classes and methods in the API as well as typical usage scenarios, code snippets, design rationales, performance discussions, and contracts, but implementation details of the API services themselves are usually omitted.
[src:graphql-js/api] It can take a number of forms, including instructional documents, tutorials, and reference works.
[src:graphql-js/api] It'll also include a variety of information types, including guides and functionalities.
[src:graphql-js/api] Restrictions and limitations on how the API can be used are also covered by the documentation.
[src:graphql-js/api] For instance, documentation for an API function could note that its parameters cannot be null, that the function itself is not thread safe.
[src:graphql-js/api] Because API documentation tends to be comprehensive, it is a challenge for writers to keep the documentation updated and for users to read it carefully, potentially yielding bugs.
[src:graphql-js/api] API documentation can be enriched with metadata information like Java annotations.
[src:graphql-js/api] This metadata can be used by the compiler, tools, and by the *run-time* environment to implement custom behaviors or custom handling.
[src:graphql-js/api] It is possible to generate API documentation in a data-driven manner.
[src:graphql-js/api] By observing many programs that use a given API, it is possible to infer the typical usages, as well the required contracts and directives.
[src:graphql-js/api] Then, templates can be used to generate natural language from the mined data.
[src:graphql-js/api] In 2010, Oracle Corporation sued Google for having distributed a new implementation of Java embedded in the Android operating system.
[src:graphql-js/api] Google had not acquired any permission to reproduce the Java API, although permission had been given to the similar OpenJDK project.
[src:graphql-js/api] Judge William Alsup ruled in the *Oracle v.
[src:graphql-js/api] Alsup's ruling was overturned in 2014 on appeal to the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit, though the question of whether such use of APIs constitutes fair use was left unresolved.
[src:graphql-js/api] In 2016, following a two-week trial, a jury determined that Google's reimplementation of the Java API constituted fair use, but Oracle vowed to appeal the decision.
[src:graphql-js/api] Oracle won on its appeal, with the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit ruling that Google's use of the APIs did not qualify for fair use.
[src:graphql-js/api] In 2019, Google appealed to the Supreme Court of the United States over both the copyrightability and fair use rulings, and the Supreme Court granted review.
[src:graphql-js/api] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the oral hearings in the case were delayed until October 2020.
[src:graphql-js/api] The case was decided by the Supreme Court in Google's favor.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] The JavaScript reference implementation for GraphQL, a query language for APIs created by Facebook.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] See more complete documentation at https://graphql.org/ and https://graphql.org/graphql-js/.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] A general overview of GraphQL is available in the README for the Specification for GraphQL.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] That overview describes a simple set of GraphQL examples that exist as tests in this repository.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] A good way to get started with this repository is to walk through that README and the corresponding tests in parallel.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] GraphQL.js provides two important capabilities: building a type schema and serving queries against that type schema.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] First, build a GraphQL type schema which maps to your codebase.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] This defines a simple schema, with one type and one field, that resolves to a fixed value.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] The `resolve` function can return a value, a promise, or an array of promises.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] A more complex example is included in the top-level tests directory.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] Then, serve the result of a query against that type schema.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] This runs a query fetching the one field defined.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] The `graphql` function will first ensure the query is syntactically and semantically valid before executing it, reporting errors otherwise.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] The `npm` branch in this repository is automatically maintained to be the last commit to `17.x.x` to pass all tests, in the same form found on npm.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] GraphQL.js is a general-purpose library and can be used both in a Node server and in the browser.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] As an example, the GraphiQL tool is built with GraphQL.js!
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] Building a project using GraphQL.js with webpack or rollup should just work and only include the portions of the library you use.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] This works because GraphQL.js is distributed with both CommonJS (`require()`) and ESModule (`import`) files.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] The `exports` map within the project `package.json` should direct runtimes and bundlers to the appropriate files.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] Tools that do not support `exports` will find the CommonJS and ESModule builds side by side, with the CommonJS code packaged in files with the `.js` extension and the ESModule build within `.mjs` files.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] Project participants must sign the free GraphQL Specification Membership agreement before making a contribution.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] You only need to do this one time, and it can be signed by individual contributors or their employers.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] To initiate the signature process please open a PR against this repo.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] The EasyCLA bot will block the merge if we still need a membership agreement from you.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] If you have issues, please email operations@graphql.org.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] If your company benefits from GraphQL and you would like to provide essential financial support for the systems and people that power our community, please also consider membership in the GraphQL Foundation.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] GraphQL.JS follows Semantic Versioning (SemVer) for its releases.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] We do not currently offer a Long-Term Support version of GraphQL.JS.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] Users are encouraged to upgrade to the latest stable version to receive the most up-to-date features, performance improvements, and security updates.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] We will announce the EOL date for a major version at least 6 months in advance.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] After a version reaches its EOL, it will no longer receive updates, even for critical security issues.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] We welcome community contributions for all versions of GraphQL.JS.
[src:graphql-js/graphql-graphql-js] However, our maintainers will primarily focus on reviewing and merging contributions for supported versions.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] Facebook started GraphQL development in 2012 and released a draft specification and reference implementation as open source in 2015.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] In 2018, GraphQL was moved to the newly established GraphQL Foundation, hosted by the non-profit Linux Foundation.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] On February 9, 2018, the GraphQL Schema Definition Language became part of the specification.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] Many popular public APIs adopted GraphQL as the default way to access them.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] These include public APIs of Facebook, GitHub, Yelp, Shopify, Google Directions API and many others.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] There is an annual GraphQL Conference featuring new developments of the protocol and organizations successfully using GraphQL.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] The event is hosted by the GraphQL Foundation with previous organizers incl.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] GraphQL supports reading, writing (mutating), and subscribing to changes to data (realtime updates – commonly implemented using WebSockets).
[src:graphql-js/graphql] A GraphQL service is created by defining types with fields, then providing functions to resolve the data for each field.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] The types and fields make up what is known as the *schema definition*.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] The functions that retrieve and map the data are called *resolvers*.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] After being validated against the schema, a GraphQL query is executed by the server.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] The server returns a result that mirrors the shape of the original query, typically as JSON.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] With GraphQL, a business domain is modeled as a graph by defining a schema; within this schema, different types of nodes and their relations are defined.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] The GraphQL type system describes what data can be queried from the API.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] The collection of those capabilities is referred to as the service's *schema* and clients can use that schema to send queries to the API that return predictable results.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] The root type of a GraphQL schema, `Query` by default, contains all of the fields that can be queried.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] Other types define the objects and fields that the GraphQL server can return.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] There are several base types, called scalars, to represent things like strings, numbers, and IDs.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] Fields are defined as nullable by default, and a trailing exclamation mark can be used to make a field non-nullable (required).
[src:graphql-js/graphql] A field can be defined as a list by wrapping the field's type in square brackets (for example, `authors: [String]`).
[src:graphql-js/graphql] A GraphQL query defines the exact shape of the data needed by the client.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] Once validated and executed by the GraphQL server, the data is returned in the same shape.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] A GraphQL mutation allows for data to be created, updated, or deleted.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] Mutations generally contain *variables*, which allow data to be passed into the server from the client.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] The mutation also defines the shape of the data that will be returned to the client after the operation is complete.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] The variables are passed as an object with fields that match the variable names in the mutation.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] Once the operation is complete, the GraphQL server will return data matching the shape defined by the mutation.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] GraphQL also supports live updates sent from the server to client in an operation called a subscription.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] Again, the client defines the shape of the data that it needs whenever an update is made.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] When a mutation is made through the GraphQL server that updates the associated field, data is sent to all subscribed clients in the format setup through the subscription.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] While there's nothing that prevents a GraphQL service from being versioned just like any other API, GraphQL takes a strong opinion on avoiding versioning by providing the tools for the continuous evolution of a GraphQL schema.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] The `@deprecated` *built-in directive* is used within the type system definition language to indicate deprecated portions of a GraphQL service's schema, such as deprecated fields on a type or deprecated enum values.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] GraphQL only returns the data that's explicitly requested, so new capabilities can be added via new types or new fields on existing types without creating a breaking change.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] This has led to a common practice of always avoiding breaking changes and serving a versionless API.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] GraphQL does not provide a full-fledged graph query language such as SPARQL, or even in dialects of SQL that support transitive closure.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] For example, a GraphQL interface that reports the parents of an individual cannot return, in a single query, the set of all their ancestors.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] GraphQL APIs can be tested manually or with automated tools issuing GraphQL requests and verifying the correctness of the results.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] Automatic test generation is also possible.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] New requests may be produced through search-based techniques due to a typed schema and introspection capabilities.
[src:graphql-js/graphql] Some of the software tools used for testing GraphQL implementations include Postman, Beeceptor, GraphiQL, Apollo Studio, GraphQL Hive, GraphQL Editor, and Step CI.
